<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="KNI01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Robert</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Knight</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> </placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">MP </occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial">
    Rpobert Knight was an MP and an associate of Horne Tooke and was linked to the Whigs. It seems probable
    that the Knights recorded at Horne Tooke's or Debrett's are Robert Knight, and there are also a number of
    entries that include some part of the first name. (Godwin notes in the 1796 Diary that he met Rt
    Knight in 1793) Both sets have been accordingly coded as this Knight. It is possible that
    Godwin also knew Richard Payne Knight, MP, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title>, but there is nothing in the Diary that
    identifies this Knight distinctively (and no entry in the 1796 list).
    
    However,  according to the 1796 list Godwin met <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="KNI02">T(homas) Knight</persName>, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title>, the actor (who features also in <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The Life of Thomas Holcroft</title>) in
    1792 - the entry is to Mr and Mrs Knight . We have worked on the presumption that  it is Thomas Knight who accounts for a number of the plain 'Knight' entries, and on
    whom Godwin calls and who calls on him, between 1792 and 1798.  From 1798 there are more frequent references to 'T Knight'  and references to 'Rt Knight' are also more common.  
    Where there is considerable uncertainty about the identity of a 'Knight' it  has been left uncoded. The Knight recorded in 1807 with Wolcot, and the Mrs
    Knight recorded in 1806 are likely to be the husband and wife who are Wolcot's landlord - wih
    Knight taking Wolcot to court for criminal conversation with his wife in 1807. These are not coded.
  
  Also unbcoded are the Knight entries on Godwin's 1795 trip to Warwickshire.
   
  
